30–":"1430–Overleden","1430–Male":"1430–Overleden","1425–Female":"1425–Overleden","1455–1520":"1455–1520","1402–Male":"1402–Overleden","1407–1440":"1407–1440","1425":"1425","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","2 July 1455":"11 juli 1455","1407":"1407","Westmill, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Powys, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1430–":"1430–Deceased","1430–Male":"1430–Deceased","1425–Female":"1425–Deceased","1455–1520":"1455–1520","1402–Male":"1402–Deceased","1407–1440":"1407–1440","1425":"1425","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","2 July 1455":"11 July 1455","1407":"1407","Westmill, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Powys, Wales, United Kingdom":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelhard</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Andre, Marcel, Pierre, Leonce, Normand, Camille, Lucien, Gilles, Henri.","English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The Middle English forms were <i>Richard</i> and <i>Rikard</i>, respectively Parisian Old French and Old Picard pronunciations of the ancient Germanic name. Middle English <i>Rikard</i> gives rise to the pet form   Rick  , whilst <i>Richard</i> has given the pet forms   Richie   and   Rich  . Both produced rhyming pet forms,   Dick   and   Hick   for <i>Rikard</i> and   Hitch   for <i>Richard</i>.","History: The LA Richard families are mainly descended from Acadian refugees in the second half of the 18th century. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Recker","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from a variant of the personal name   Richard  . This surname is very rare in East Frisia.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>recke</i> ‘stretch, route, hedge’, or a habitational name for someone from Recke, near Osnabrück."]},{"name":"Ricard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Andre, Armand, Normand, Raoul, Adelard, Adrien, Amedee, Damien, Fernand, Francois, Germaine.","French: variant of   Richard  . Compare   Recor  ,   Record  ,   Recore  , and   Ricord  .","Channel Islands (Guernsey): variant of   Rickard  , the characteristic Norman pronunciation of <i>Richard</i>."]},{"name":"Ricardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Roberto, Carlos, Angel, Jorge, Ramon, Ediberto, Guillermo, Joaquin, Juana.","Potuguese and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Ricardo</i>, an equivalent of   Richard  .","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the name in 1 above at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."]},{"name":"Rick","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire and Lincolnshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Rick</i>, a pet form of   Richard  . Compare   Rich   2.","German: from a short form of any of the ancient Germanic personal names formed with <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>ri(c)k</i> ‘enclosed land, fence’, or from <i>reke</i> ‘row, strip of trees’."]},{"name":"Riccardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Salvatore, Angelo, Vito, Antonio, Carmine, Domenico, Francesca.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Riccardo</i>, an equivalent of   Richard  ."]},{"name":"Pritchard","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Rhisiart</i> ‘son of Richard’(see   Richard  )."]},{"name":"Reick","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Helmuth.","German:","from a medieval personal name, a short form of   Richard  , or less commonly of some other compound name with this first element."]},{"name":"Reichard","meanings":["German: from an ancient Germanic personal name (see   Richard  ). This surname (and its variants) has also been adopted by Jews."]},{"name":"Reisert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Mathias.","German: variant of <b>Reissert</b>, a variant of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ricohard</i> (see   Richard  )."]},{"name":"Reitz","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place near Stolpe in Pomerania called Reitz.","German: from a late medieval pet form of the personal name   Richard   or <i>Heinrich</i> (see   Henry  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Raytse</i>, of ancient Germanic origin."]}]},{"name":"Bedo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>bod</i> ‘messenger, tidings’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bedo ap Richard was born in 1430, in Powys, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Richard ap Howell, was 28 and his mother, Joan Button, was 23. He married Mawd Verch Levan Frychan. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1430–":"1430–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud"